07065nam a22010695i 9780823294299DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232942997 a10.1515/97808232942992doi  a(DE-B1597)577491  a(OCoLC)1247157971  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aB105.I3bL58 2021 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a121/.422300aLiving with Concepts :bAnthropology in the Grip of Reality /ced. by Marco Motta, Andrew Brandel. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThinking from Elsewhere00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: Life with Concepts -- t1 Concepts of the Ordinary -- t2 How Life Makes a Conversation of Us: Ontology, Ethics, and Responsive Anthropology -- t3 Crisscrossing Concepts: Anthropology and Knowledge-Making -- t4 The Potencie of Text: Shifting Concepts of Myth and Literature -- t5 How Social Are Our Concepts? -- t6 Living with Zombies: Forms of Death at the Core of the Ordinary -- t7 Creating Worlds: Imagination, Interpretation, and the Subjunctive -- t8 The Life Course of Concepts -- t9 On Sorcery: Life with the Concept -- t10 How Ethical Is Our Life with Concepts? Reflections on Shared Medical Decision Making -- t11 In the Know: The Pain of the Other in Torture Rehabilitation -- tAcknowledgments -- tReferences -- tList of Contributors -- tName Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume examines an often taken for granted concept—that of the concept itself. How do we picture what concepts are, what they do, how they arise in the course of everyday life? Challenging conventional approaches that treat concepts as mere tools at our disposal for analysis, or as straightforwardly equivalent to signs to be deciphered, the anthropologists and philosophers in this volume turn instead to the ways concepts are already intrinsically embedded in our forms of life and how they constitute the very substrate of our existence as humans who lead lives in language.Attending to our ordinary lives with concepts requires not an ascent from the rough ground of reality into the skies of theory, but rather acceptance of the fact that thinking is congenital to living with and through concepts. The volume offers a critical and timely intervention into both contemporary philosophy and anthropological theory by unsettling the distinction between thought and reality that continues to be too often assumed and showing how the supposed need to grasp reality may be replaced by an acknowledgement that we are in its grip. Contributors: Jocelyn Benoist, Andrew Brandel, Michael Cordey, Veena Das, Rasmus Dyring and Thomas Schwarz Wentzer, Michael D. Jackson, Michael Lambek, Sandra Laugier, Marco Motta, Michael J. Puett, and Lotte Buch Segal  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aConcepts. 0aIdeals (Philosophy). 4aAnthropology. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aconcepts.  aepistemology.  aethics.  aethnography.  aordinary language philosophy.  aphilosophical anthropology.  aphilosophy.  arealism.  atranslation.1 aBenoist, Jocelyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandel, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandel, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuch Segal, Lotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCordey, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas, Veena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/